try and be as intuitive as

00:11:24.140 --> 00:11:24.990
possible, so people come.

00:11:24.990 --> 00:11:25.250
They look.

00:11:25.250 --> 00:11:26.990
And they say, OK, this
is the effect line.

00:11:26.990 --> 00:11:29.310
I'm supposed to press Play
so that it will start.

00:11:29.310 --> 00:11:32.350
So it was also trying to be as
clear as possible, but also

00:11:32.350 --> 00:11:34.614
trying to be as inviting
as possible.

00:11:34.614 --> 00:11:36.994
MICHAEL SVERDLIN: Actually, one
of the most interesting

00:11:36.994 --> 00:11:39.725
decisions that we came
to, I think, the

00:11:39.725 --> 00:11:41.206
day before the event.

00:11:41.206 --> 00:11:44.608
Our original plan was to put a
laptop in front of the people,

00:11:44.608 --> 00:11:45.580
the visitors.

00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:50.060
But we decided to only put a
mouse there so that people

00:11:50.060 --> 00:11:54.270
will be very constrained
in what they do.

00:11:54.270 --> 00:11:58.670
And actually, people still
can't wait to escape our

00:11:58.670 --> 00:12:02.180
sandbox of [INAUDIBLE], but--

00:12:02.180 --> 00:12:03.599
and start playing.

00:12:03.599 --> 00:12:06.440
So we understand that
it was really

00:12:06.440 --> 00:12:07.905
easier with only a mouse.

00:12:07.905 --> 00:12:11.437
People knew exactly what
they needed to do.

00:12:11.437 --> 00:12:12.820
IDO GREEN: Thanks.

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:16.486
And so we talked about
the artistic aspects.

00:12:16.486 --> 00:12:19.414
Maybe we can talk a bit more
about the technical aspects or

00:12:19.414 --> 00:12:21.400
what were the main challenges.

00:12:21.400 --> 00:12:24.552
MICHAEL SVERDLIN: Well, the main
challenge in our piece of

00:12:24.552 --> 00:12:28.666
work is we are pushing two video
streams, which is pretty

00:12:28.666 --> 00:12:33.510
hard even on mobile CPUs,
a browser, of course.

00:12:33.510 --> 00:12:37.755
And even more, we're doing
pair frame effects, like

00:12:37.755 --> 00:12:39.599
[INAUDIBLE]

00:12:39.599 --> 00:12:42.420
and inverting colors.

00:12:42.420 --> 00:12:49.386
And doing everything in about
33 milliseconds was hard on

00:12:49.386 --> 00:12:51.302
some of the computers
we tried it in.

00:12:51.302 --> 00:12:55.134
The kind of computer that was
provided for us was only an 83

00:12:55.134 --> 00:12:58.280
CPU, and it kind of lagged.

00:12:58.280 --> 00:13:01.742
It wasn't a smooth 30
frames per second.

00:13:01.742 --> 00:13:05.890
It was more like 15, 20
frames per second.

00:13:05.890 --> 00:13:10.160
And as you pile on the effect,
it gets worse and worse.

00:13:10.160 --> 00:13:13.990
So that was a real challenge.

00:13:13.990 --> 00:13:18.830
And some other challenges were
syncing the audio and video,

00:13:18.830 --> 00:13:21.688
which was very important
for Emmanuel for the--

00:13:21.688 --> 00:13:22.632
EMMANUEL WITZTHUM: For
the experience.

00:13:22.632 --> 00:13:23.576
MICHAEL SVERDLIN: --for
the experience.

00:13:23.576 --> 00:13:25.560
And it's totally
understandable.

00:13:25.560 --> 00:13:30.452
But we couldn't actually have
it screen from the network

00:13:30.452 --> 00:13:33.136
because then everything will
download at different times.

00:13:33.136 --> 00:13:36.756
It's about five audio streams
and two video streams.

00:13:36.756 --> 00:13:39.000
So they'll never sync.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:43.308
So we ended up running it on the
local web server and then

00:13:43.308 --> 00:13:49.362
copying it, saving the actual
file into a remote server, for

00:13:49.362 --> 00:13:54.302
replaying stuff like that, which
was actually one of the

00:13:54.302 --> 00:13:58.254
awesome features that I don't
think anyone ever used.

00:13:58.254 --> 00:13:59.736
But they're actually there.

00:13:59.736 --> 00:14:02.206
You can replay whatever
decisions you

00:14:02.206 --> 00:14:04.410
