00:18:08.960 --> 00:18:11.435
could share a bit?

00:18:11.435 --> 00:18:13.415
MICHAEL SVERDLIN: Uri, you
could do your talk?

00:18:13.415 --> 00:18:14.405
Or I'll talk.

00:18:14.405 --> 00:18:15.395
URI SHAKED: All right.

00:18:15.395 --> 00:18:20.350
So first of all, let me tell
you about the project I

00:18:20.350 --> 00:18:21.910
participated in.

00:18:21.910 --> 00:18:25.790
Emmanuel gave you
a teaser before.

00:18:25.790 --> 00:18:29.525
In my project, the direction was
by moving inside the room.

00:18:29.525 --> 00:18:31.465
The project was called--

00:18:31.465 --> 00:18:34.380
still called the SoundTracker.

00:18:34.380 --> 00:18:40.490
And the idea behind it is to
let the participants create

00:18:40.490 --> 00:18:45.440
music by moving around
inside a room.

00:18:45.440 --> 00:18:49.774
So usually, it takes a musical
instrument and years of

00:18:49.774 --> 00:18:52.546
training in order to play
something that is

00:18:52.546 --> 00:18:56.280
clever to the ears.

00:18:56.280 --> 00:18:59.780
So we wanted to create an
experience that will let

00:18:59.780 --> 00:19:05.040
anybody just walk into the
room and join into a live

00:19:05.040 --> 00:19:10.760
orchestra, interacting with
other people in this same

00:19:10.760 --> 00:19:15.920
space and creating music
as a consequence of

00:19:15.920 --> 00:19:19.420
moving inside the room.

00:19:19.420 --> 00:19:23.996
So before I'm going to talk
about the technology, let's

00:19:23.996 --> 00:19:25.460
talk a little about--

00:19:25.460 --> 00:19:30.828
I will tell you a little about
the obstacles we had.

00:19:30.828 --> 00:19:32.780
We had many of them.

00:19:32.780 --> 00:19:37.550
First of all, we worked
with a music artist.

00:19:37.550 --> 00:19:42.809
And he wanted to create as
many tracks as eight.

00:19:42.809 --> 00:19:48.030
But then we realized that the
average person without musical

00:19:48.030 --> 00:19:52.200
training can't tell what his
specific role is when there

00:19:52.200 --> 00:19:55.380
are too many instruments
playing at once.

00:19:55.380 --> 00:20:00.330
So we had to cut down to four.

00:20:00.330 --> 00:20:04.494
And that actually solved a lot
of problems that we had.

00:20:04.494 --> 00:20:09.950
In order to find out where the
people are in every specific

00:20:09.950 --> 00:20:13.422
moment-- what is their position
inside the room--

00:20:13.422 --> 00:20:17.390
we tried several approaches.

00:20:17.390 --> 00:20:22.350
And every single approach-- we
had a problem that the more

00:20:22.350 --> 00:20:26.900
people we had, the approach
failed more times.

00:20:26.900 --> 00:20:31.940
Because people were hiding
by each other.

00:20:31.940 --> 00:20:36.970
And we tried several
alternatives.

00:20:36.970 --> 00:20:42.426
The beginning, we started with
putting hats on the people, on

00:20:42.426 --> 00:20:49.656
their heads, and using a camera
above to recognize the

00:20:49.656 --> 00:20:53.355
location of each of the
people in the room.

00:20:53.355 --> 00:20:58.559
We tried to take advantage of
the open source OpenCV, Open

00:20:58.559 --> 00:20:59.860
Computer Vision.

00:20:59.860 --> 00:21:02.350
That is a library.

00:21:02.350 --> 00:21:06.515
But it wasn't accurate enough.

00:21:06.515 --> 00:21:09.425
So we tried a whole different
approach.

00:21:09.425 --> 00:21:14.275
Instead of using simple image
accumulation to recognize the

00:21:14.275 --> 00:21:17.670
hats and LEDs-- the light
emitting LEDs

00:21:17.670 --> 00:21:20.590
we had on the hats--

00:21:20.590 --> 00:21:25.340
we changed to using full
body rests with

00:21:25.340 --> 00:21:27.720
some sort of QR codes.

00:21:27.720 --> 00:21:31.340
And then we found a great open
source-- not open source, but

00:21:31.340 --> 00:21:38.070
free library from Qualcomm
that's called Vuforia.

00:21:38.070 --> 00:21:43.515
And it's provided free for
both Android and iOS.

00:21:43.515 --> 00:21:49.480
So we shifted our approach from
using computer processing

00:21:49.480 --> 00:21:54.350
to actually do the processing
on a set of Android devices.

00:21:54.350 --> 00:22:00.154
We had Android tablets hanging
all around the room from

00:22:00.154 --> 00:22:06.080
different provisions, and they
constant are taking pictures

00:22:06.080 --> 00:22:10.100
of the room and analyzing the
pictures, looking for these QR

00:22:10.100 --> 00:22:14.370
codes, using this
Qualcomm SDK.

00:22:14.370 --> 00:22:18.734
And then we used a main
server, which tried to

00:22:18.734 --> 00:22:23.750
integrate the information from
all the tablets and create a

00:22:23.750 --> 00:22:29.818
track of music by letting each
person control their

00:22:29.818 --> 00:22:31.264
individual instrument--

00:22:31.264 --> 00:22:36.700
like drums, guitar, piano,
synthesizer--

00:22:36.700 --> 00:22:39.446
using his position and the
state of his movement.

00:22:43.440 --> 00:22:47.904
We will add videos where you
will be able to see people

00:22:47.904 --> 00:22:50.264
interacting with it.

00:22:50.264 --> 00:22:55.980
Now one of the most interesting
aspects for us was

00:22:55.980 --> 00:23:00.300
the fact that people didn't
quite interact

00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:02.700
with it as we expected.

00:23:02.700 --> 00:23:09.180
We thought that people will try
to come into the room and

00:23:09.180 --> 00:23:12.684
then will just walk around
and see what happens.

00:23:12.684 --> 00:23:16.460
And we found out that different
kinds of people

00:23:16.460 --> 00:23:18.380
interacted in different ways.

00:23:18.380 --> 00:23:25.450
For example, there were people
who just walked every one step

00:23:25.450 --> 00:23:28.132
forward, then looked what
happened, another step

00:23:28.132 --> 00:23:30.315
forward, then looked
what happened.

00:23:30.315 --> 00:23:34.922
And the system was not designed
to identify such

00:23:34.922 --> 00:23:36.135
small movements.

00:23:36.135 --> 00:23:43.130
So we put shapes on the edges of
the floor in order to make

00:23:43.130 --> 00:23:45.050
them move from shape to shape.

00:23:45.050 --> 00:23:48.726
So they tried to jump between
the shapes without--

00:23:48.726 --> 00:23:50.970
they turned it into
a kind of game--

00:23:50.970 --> 00:23:58.480
without touching the floor or
sort of swimming the air or do

00:23:58.480 --> 00:24:00.731
really cool things.

00:24:00.731 --> 00:24:06.695
And then we found that our best
audience was children,

00:24:06.695 --> 00:24:10.174
who really enjoyed running
all around.

00:24:10.174 --> 00:24:15.144
And I'm not sure whether they
really understood the relation

00:24:15.144 --> 00:24:18.130
between their position
and the music.

00:24:18.130 --> 00:24:18.920
But they enjoyed it.

00:24:18.920 --> 00:24:21.290
That's for sure.

00:24:21.290 --> 00:24:25.140
And also there were sort of some
old people who started

00:24:25.140 --> 00:24:28.870
looking around and
then seeing--

00:24:28.870 --> 00:24:32.600
you saw like, OK, this
is the real color.

00:24:32.600 --> 00:24:34.540
Guys, this is different.

00:24:34.540 --> 00:24:38.420
This is not just walking from
one room to another and

00:24:38.420 --> 00:24:40.845
watching another painting
and saying wow.

00:24:40.845 --> 00:24:43.270
This is really getting
us active,

00:24:43.270 --> 00:24:47.480
getting us the full angle.

00:24:47.480 --> 00:24:51.738
So that was the best thing
about the project, seeing

00:24:51.738 --> 00:24:56.260
people who were interacting
immediately with it, who were

00:24:56.260 --> 00:24:59.690
enjoying it, were starting
to dance around

00:24:59.690 --> 00:25:02.140
and do crazy things.

00:25:02.140 --> 00:25:06.550
And I think that's what
we wanted to achieve.

00:25:06.550 --> 00:25:10.490
And I think that we
succeeded in that.

00:25:10.490 --> 00:25:13.540
IDO GREEN: And you were just
speaking about the technical

00:25:13.540 --> 00:25:14.687
stack that you used.

00:25:14.687 --> 00:25:16.120
URI SHAKED: Yeah.

00:25:16.120 --> 00:25:22.355
So for the audio, we wanted
the audio to follow the

00:25:22.355 --> 00:25:25.210
location of people
in the room.

00:25:25.210 --> 00:25:31.400
So if they are, for example,
controlling the piano, we

00:25:31.400 --> 00:25:36.116
wanted them to hear the piano
from the same position as they

00:25:36.116 --> 00:25:38.920
were standing in, from
the same speaker

00:25:38.920 --> 00:25:41.900
where they were standing.

00:25:41.900 --> 00:25:48.320
So we had to use the OpenAL
library that provides a 3D

00:25:48.320 --> 00:25:50.390
audio spot.

00:25:50.390 --> 00:25:56.420
And in order to use the OpenAL
library from within Java, we

00:25:56.420 --> 00:26:00.360
had to create Java bindings
to the library.

00:26:00.360 --> 00:26:06.130
There were some very old Java
bindings which didn't work

00:26:06.130 --> 00:26:09.195
well with our environment.

00:26:09.195 --> 00:26:13.360
So we started a new open source
project that is Java

00:26:13.360 --> 00:26:16.790
bindings for OpenAL,
Java OpenAL.

00:26:16.790 --> 00:26:24.140
And this is a result
of the Devart.

00:26:24.140 --> 00:26:29.530
We now have it on GDocs
so we can--

00:26:29.530 --> 00:26:32.470
IDO GREEN: Yeah, we'll show a
bit later some of the project.

00:26:32.470 --> 00:26:36.190
URI SHAKED: Check it out
if you are interested.

00:26:36.190 --> 00:26:39.548
And we also used
the FluidSynth.

00:26:39.548 --> 00:26:47.420
It's a sound synthesizer that
lets you synthesize sounds

00:26:47.420 --> 00:26:52.470
from musical instruments
on the fly.

00:26:52.470 --> 00:26:57.733
So it was like the brain behind
the sound engine.

00:26:57.733 --> 00:27:00.691
And we fed the position
information.

00:27:00.691 --> 00:27:06.360
We translated it into a sequence
of play a note on

00:27:06.360 --> 00:27:10.058
this instrument, stop playing
the note and so on.

00:27:10.058 --> 00:27:12.550
And we fed that into
the FluidSynth.

00:27:12.550 --> 00:27:14.970
It created the sound stream.

00:27:14.970 --> 00:27:18.698
And then we took that sound
stream and fed it into OpenAL

00:27:18.698 --> 00:27:23.820
in order to create the 3D sound
experience, where each

00:27:23.820 --> 00:27:27.210
player controls a specific
instrument, both in the

00:27:27.210 --> 00:27:30.736
position and in the way that
instrument's placed.

00:27:30.736 --> 00:27:32.712
IDO GREEN: Nice.

