00:28:27.830 --> 00:28:29.285
EMMANUEL WITZTHUM: Begin with
the technical approach.

00:28:29.285 --> 00:28:30.255
IDO GREEN: OK.

00:28:30.255 --> 00:28:32.710
What is the most important thing
to pay attention to?

00:28:32.710 --> 00:28:36.400
URI SHAKED: Well, I'm not sure
whether it's truly technical

00:28:36.400 --> 00:28:38.090
or artistic.

00:28:38.090 --> 00:28:43.405
But what we learned is it's very
important to let people--

00:28:43.405 --> 00:28:47.365
if you are building something
interactive, as we did in our

00:28:47.365 --> 00:28:51.000
both projects, let people, your
friends, your family,

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:55.961
interact with the system in an
early stage in order to figure

00:28:55.961 --> 00:28:58.265
out whether they are interacting
with it in the way

00:28:58.265 --> 00:28:59.340
that you planned.

00:28:59.340 --> 00:29:02.362
Or maybe there is a
much better way to

00:29:02.362 --> 00:29:04.920
interact with it.

00:29:04.920 --> 00:29:10.516
So we will be able to build a
system to be the most fun--

00:29:10.516 --> 00:29:13.668
or whatever your goal is--

00:29:13.668 --> 00:29:19.300
as you build it, and not just
build it as you think it will

00:29:19.300 --> 00:29:24.300
be appropriated and then get it
and see that it is used in

00:29:24.300 --> 00:29:27.610
different ways you didn't
anticipate.

00:29:27.610 --> 00:29:28.970
IDO GREEN: So, Emmanuel.

00:29:28.970 --> 00:29:30.800
EMMANUEL WITZTHUM: Not me.

00:29:30.800 --> 00:29:35.474
MICHAEL SVERDLIN: Well, I think
my top advice is think

00:29:35.474 --> 00:29:36.470
about the user.

00:29:36.470 --> 00:29:40.952
Think about who is going to
stand in front of your project

00:29:40.952 --> 00:29:43.940
or the experience
you will have.

00:29:43.940 --> 00:29:47.590
And you should understand
that the crowd--

00:29:47.590 --> 00:29:50.964
if you're a developer, the crowd
you see there is not

00:29:50.964 --> 00:29:52.860
your usual tech-y crowd.

00:29:52.860 --> 00:29:57.097
There are a lot of people who
are not fluent in computers.

00:29:57.097 --> 00:29:59.600
And you need to make
it as smooth of an

00:29:59.600 --> 00:30:00.850
experience as possible.

00:30:03.458 --> 00:30:04.919
That's my top tip.

00:30:04.919 --> 00:30:08.328
And also, of course, have fun
and do something crazy, which

00:30:08.328 --> 00:30:10.290
is very important.

00:30:10.290 --> 00:30:11.806
EMMANUEL WITZTHUM: I'll
take that last

00:30:11.806 --> 00:30:14.060
crazy thing and yeah.

00:30:14.060 --> 00:30:15.650
Be open to experiment.

00:30:15.650 --> 00:30:16.930
Be open to it being a process.

00:30:16.930 --> 00:30:19.230
Don't feel that you're coming
into a project and you're

00:30:19.230 --> 00:30:21.720
supposed to tell the developer
what to do or have the

00:30:21.720 --> 00:30:23.250
developer tell you what to do.

00:30:23.250 --> 00:30:24.600
You're there to create
something together.

00:30:24.600 --> 00:30:29.260
Think of A plus B makes C. And
the public can be the C. You

00:30:29.260 --> 00:30:31.570
guys can be the C. The end
product could be the C.

00:30:31.570 --> 00:30:36.392
Everything can be a C. But the
idea behind it is to try and

00:30:36.392 --> 00:30:38.588
experiment and to try
to do something new.

00:30:38.588 --> 00:30:40.540
And Devart is exactly,
I think, that.

00:30:40.540 --> 00:30:41.516
IDO GREEN: No, absolutely.

